name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: These free test kits are for those who may have been exposed to COVID-19, who have symptoms of COVID-19, or who want to take extra steps to protect vulnerable family and friends. They are not for routine employment testing, pre-travel testing, or school quarantine/isolation.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: We offer 2 kinds of testing...  2. *** BINAXNOW AT-HOME RAPID TESTING: a limited number of BinaxNow At-Home Rapid Test Kits,  available for pick-up during scheduled Health Department testing dates Mon, Wed, Fri from 9:30AM-12:30PM, while supplies last.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: Self-collection testing is administered on-site, or take-home test kits are available for testing on your schedule. Test results are available in 2-4 days. These tests may be used for routine employment testing, pre-travel testing, or school quarantine/isolation.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: We offer 2 kinds of testing...  1. AZOVA SALIVA TESTING: PCR testing for COVID-19 using the FDA-authorized Azova saliva test kit (which is more comfortable than traditional nasal swab).

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: The best way to protect yourself and others from COVID-19, including Omicron and other variants, is to get vaccinated, get a booster as soon as you are eligible, get tested if you have symptoms, and wear a mask in indoor public settings or crowded environments.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: Until we know more, remember that any COVID-19 infection can be life threatening, particularly if you are unvaccinated or have underlying medical conditions.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: Studies are happening now to determine whether Omicron is more or less contagious, or poses a greater or lesser health risk, than other variants.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: In the U.S., several cases have been identified, including 3 in Maryland.

name: Howard County Health Department
tweet: Here's what we know so far: Omicron is a new variant of the virus that causes COVID-19.
